{"add":{"doc":{"id":"47e89e73999a32c0e793c673fdba38db23474104499b590db0258afdc950c00e","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/b/a/0ba118c2d8c335e2f96292a1e771bc09.png","previous":[],"after":["In July 1739 he made his first contribution to the field of mathematics, pointing out the errors he had detected in L'analyse démontrée (published 1708 by Charles René Reynaud) in a communication addressed to the Académie des Sciences. At the time L'analyse démontrée was a standard work, which d'Alembert himself had used to study the foundations of mathematics. D'Alembert was also a Latin scholar of some note and worked in the latter part of his life on a superb translation of Tacitus, for which he received wide praise including that of Denis Diderot."]}}}